e’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":5,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Nicholas Hesketh was born in 1377, in Rufford, Lancashire, England as the son of Thomas Hesketh and Margaret Bannester. He married Lady Margaret Ward of Minshull in 1389. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1416, in his hometown, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1377–1416":"1377–1416","1407–1459":"1407–1459","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1459":"1459","1389":"1389","1377":"1377","from about 1250 to 1650":"from about 1250 to 1650","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1407":"1407","1417":"1416","1416":"1416","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"137